SEMANTIC PRINCIPLE (universal, applies to ALL objects, not just events):
- Verb CREATES/SETS/WRITES/DELETES an entity (destructive/mutating action)
  → maps to operative verb (create/set/write/delete/move/send/share).
  Examples: «book appointment» = create events (ADR 0128), «send mail» =
  send messages, «delete file» = delete files, «create folder» = create dirs,
  «share the doc with X» = share files (outbound consent).
- Verb ASKS/PROPOSES/SUGGESTS/SHOWS (inquiry, read-only) → read.
  Textual synthesis of the result happens in planner's final_answer; there
  is NO `describe_<object>` executor for most objects (exception:
  describe_numbers for numeric list pure-compute stats). Examples:
  «propose 3 times» = read events, «show me X files» = read files,
  «what are N free?» = read events.
- If the sentence mixes both senses («if there's a slot book the meeting»)
  the winning intent is the MUTATING verb (create for events post ADR 0128)
  — the availability check is handled at planner level as first-action
  (read_events).
NOTE ON events vs proposals:
- events = CALENDAR APPOINTMENTS / MEETINGS (user-facing agenda).
  "book/schedule/create appointment|meeting|reminder" = create events (ADR 0128).
- proposals = INTERNAL Metnos synth/introvertiva proposals (suggestions
  to improve the catalog itself). Never the user-facing intent.
  If the query mentions "appointment/meeting/booking" it is NOT proposals.
SINGLE vs CONTAINER RULE:
When the query distinguishes between a SINGLE element and a CONTAINER (folder,
group, set), the object is the container if the action treats the container
as a unit (sum/count/sort PER container, work ON the
container), otherwise it is the element.
- Action on the element (reading, criterion, hash, rendering content,
  modifying a single one): object = element (files, messages, lines, ...).
- Action on the container (population, aggregate size, tree
  structure, top containers, creation/deletion of the container itself):
  object = container (dirs, ...).
"find .py" → files (criterion on individuals).
"find the largest directories" → dirs (on containers).
"count totals aggregating by folder" → dirs (aggregated on the container).
"total size of the path" → dirs (on the container).
"subdirectory structure" → dirs (on the container).
"create the folder" → dirs (action on the container itself).

COMPOUND (MULTIPLE ACTIONS IN SEQUENCE):
If the request contains MULTIPLE sequential actions (typically "do X then Y",
"find ... and write ...", "take ... and put ...", "download ... and send ..."),
respond with a JSON ARRAY of {verb,object} objects, ONE per action, IN execution
ORDER. Each clause carries ITS OWN real object (the object THAT action operates
on), NEVER one global object repeated. Single action → one JSON object, not an array.
Compound examples:
"find the processes using the most memory and write a report" →
  [{"verb":"find","object":"processes"},{"verb":"write","object":"files"}]
"read the closed issues and put them in a spreadsheet" →
  [{"verb":"find","object":"issues"},{"verb":"create","object":"files"}]
"download the invoices from the site and email them to me" →
  [{"verb":"find","object":"urls"},{"verb":"send","object":"messages"}]
"find the 2020 photos, compress them and send them to me" →
  [{"verb":"find","object":"files"},{"verb":"compress","object":"files"},{"verb":"send","object":"messages"}]

Respond ONLY with the JSON, no prose.

